00:04:37.970 --> 00:04:40.750 align:middle line:84%
So the first welfare theorem
says that any Walrasian

00:04:40.750 --> 00:04:43.270 align:middle line:90%
equilibrium is optimal.

00:04:43.270 --> 00:04:48.740 align:middle line:84%
And the proof is
by contradiction.

00:04:48.740 --> 00:04:50.680 align:middle line:90%
Suppose it's not optimal.

00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:53.200 align:middle line:84%
Then, there's
something that's weakly

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:57.880 align:middle line:84%
preferred by some households and
strictly preferred by others.

00:04:57.880 --> 00:05:03.580 align:middle line:84%
And then, as was just said, the
strictly preferred by others

00:05:03.580 --> 00:05:09.250 align:middle line:84%
means it could not have been
available, because it otherwise

00:05:09.250 --> 00:05:12.130 align:middle line:84%
would have been purchased
in Walrasian equilibria.

00:05:12.130 --> 00:05:15.790 align:middle line:84%
And then, we had a little lemma
that was quite subtle even

00:05:15.790 --> 00:05:20.360 align:middle line:84%
for those guys who weekly prefer
the alternative allocation,

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:25.650 align:middle line:84%
they too would be
spending weekly more.

00:05:25.650 --> 00:05:29.540 align:middle line:84%
And so we get the
total expenditure

00:05:29.540 --> 00:05:32.370 align:middle line:84%
summing up over
all the households

00:05:32.370 --> 00:05:36.450 align:middle line:84%
that would be necessary
at the competitive prices

00:05:36.450 --> 00:05:39.540 align:middle line:84%
to achieve the alternative
allocation to be strictly

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:43.590 align:middle line:84%
greater than what is being spent
in the competitive allocation.

00:05:43.590 --> 00:05:49.020 align:middle line:84%
Then, we add that to
profit maximization.

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:56.840 align:middle line:84%
And we get a relationship, a
strict inequality relationship,

00:05:56.840 --> 00:06:00.350 align:middle line:84%
which at the end of the day
said that the allocation

00:06:00.350 --> 00:06:03.170 align:middle line:90%
in the alternative--

00:06:03.170 --> 00:06:07.010 align:middle line:84%
allocation that's supposed
to be Pareto dominating

00:06:07.010 --> 00:06:10.630 align:middle line:90%
is not resource-feasible.

00:06:10.630 --> 00:06:13.100 align:middle line:84%
But the definition
of Pareto optimality

00:06:13.100 --> 00:06:20.310 align:middle line:84%
is that there is a dominating--
if something's not optimal,

00:06:20.310 --> 00:06:23.410 align:middle line:84%
it can be dominated by
something that is feasible.

00:06:23.410 --> 00:06:26.700 align:middle line:84%
So the feasibility part
will be contradicted,

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:29.490 align:middle line:90%
and that was the proof.

00:06:29.490 --> 00:06:31.730 align:middle line:84%
OK, so you'll see
this theorem again

00:06:31.730 --> 00:06:36.890 align:middle line:84%
when we get to that last
lecture on monetary economics.

00:06:36.890 --> 00:06:43.060 align:middle line:84%
It's going to turn out that
under certain conditions

00:06:43.060 --> 00:06:48.380 align:middle line:84%
like having overlapping
generations of people

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:55.710 align:middle line:84%
so that no person lives forever,
but time goes on forever,

00:06:55.710 --> 00:07:00.300 align:middle line:84%
that that's enough to
make the first welfare

00:07:00.300 --> 00:07:04.860 align:middle line:84%
theorem fail, surprisingly, when
we get into monetary economics.

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:10.110 align:middle line:84%
And the proof then
begs the issue

00:07:10.110 --> 00:07:12.990 align:middle line:84%
of where this proof
is breaking down.

00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:16.770 align:middle line:84%
And it's going to turn
out that the valuation

00:07:16.770 --> 00:07:21.030 align:middle line:84%
of the alternative bundle at the
competitive equilibrium prices

00:07:21.030 --> 00:07:23.880 align:middle line:90%
costs an infinite amount.

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:26.100 align:middle line:84%
So we implicitly
assume everything

00:07:26.100 --> 00:07:29.970 align:middle line:84%
is finite in this finite
dimension of Euclidean space.

00:07:29.970 --> 00:07:33.390 align:middle line:90%
