00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:03.500 align:middle line:84%
So the second welfare
theorem states

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:07.340 align:middle line:84%
that any Pareto
optimal allocation

00:08:07.340 --> 00:08:11.120 align:middle line:84%
can be achieved by
some price equilibrium,

00:08:11.120 --> 00:08:15.800 align:middle line:84%
assuming that you can shift
endowment point under exchange.

00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:20.780 align:middle line:84%
And so in the Lagrangian
maximization problem,

00:08:20.780 --> 00:08:23.030 align:middle line:84%
basically, you're finding
the actual endowment

00:08:23.030 --> 00:08:27.200 align:middle line:84%
that will give you the
correct price equilibrium

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:31.500 align:middle line:84%
corresponding to the desired
Pareto optimal allocation.

00:08:31.500 --> 00:08:33.020 align:middle line:84%
And you can do
that just by first

00:08:33.020 --> 00:08:39.230 align:middle line:84%
solving the Pareto problem to
get the first order conditions

00:08:39.230 --> 00:08:40.070 align:middle line:90%
reallocations.

00:08:40.070 --> 00:08:43.169 align:middle line:84%
And then, you can solve the
Walrasian equilibrium problem--

00:08:43.169 --> 00:08:46.850 align:middle line:84%
so the consumer and the firm
side problem separately.

00:08:46.850 --> 00:08:49.400 align:middle line:84%
And then, you just match the
first order of conditions.

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:51.650 align:middle line:84%
So the appropriate parameters,
like the shadow prices,

00:08:51.650 --> 00:08:55.640 align:middle line:84%
need to equal the prices
in the price equilibrium--

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:57.600 align:middle line:90%
stuff like that.

00:08:57.600 --> 00:09:01.040 align:middle line:84%
And you can show that all these
things exist in our system.

00:09:01.040 --> 00:09:03.380 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Perfect, yep.

00:09:03.380 --> 00:09:06.870 align:middle line:84%
The key is the
Lagrangian method,

00:09:06.870 --> 00:09:12.830 align:middle line:84%
which under convexity in sets
and concavity in functions

00:09:12.830 --> 00:09:16.110 align:middle line:84%
makes the first order conditions
necessary and sufficient.

00:09:16.110 --> 00:09:19.220 align:middle line:84%
So to find a solution,
all you need to do

00:09:19.220 --> 00:09:24.060 align:middle line:84%
is find variables and
shadow prices that satisfy

00:09:24.060 --> 00:09:25.380 align:middle line:90%
those first order conditions.

00:09:25.380 --> 00:09:29.970 align:middle line:84%
We have the obvious candidate,
because we start with a Pareto

00:09:29.970 --> 00:09:32.190 align:middle line:90%
optimal allocation.

00:09:32.190 --> 00:09:36.000 align:middle line:84%
So we just compare what we need
for the Walrasian allocation

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:39.830 align:middle line:84%
to what we already have
from the Pareto problem--

00:09:39.830 --> 00:09:44.970 align:middle line:84%
allocation, and choose
prices, and Lagrange

00:09:44.970 --> 00:09:47.370 align:middle line:84%
multipliers, and
so on accordingly.

00:09:47.370 --> 00:09:50.050 align:middle line:90%
So your answer was perfect.

